&lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/sociology/domains/work/domains/governance/terms/norm-conflict/>
  rdf:type schema:Article ;
  schema:url &lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/sociology/domains/work/domains/governance/terms/norm-conflict/> ;
  schema:name "Norm Conflict" ;
  schema:description "A NormConflict is a triple (N₁, N₂, R) — two norms N₁ and N₂ whose simultaneous satisfaction is impossible at history t (their required outputs are incompatible in H_t), and a resolution rule R that determines which norm yields. The defining structure: N₁ requires a ∈ H*_t and N₂ requires b ∈ H*_t but a ∧ b = ⊥ (incompatible elements). Without R, the normative system is inconsistent at t — its nucleus demands the impossible. With R, the conflict is resolved by priority: one norm's output enters H*_t; the other is defeated." ;
  schema:datePublished "2026-03-20" ;
  schema:dateModified "2026-03-20" ;
  schema:about &lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/sociology/domains/work/domains/governance/terms/norm-conflict/> ;
  rdfs:seeAlso "Norm, NormativeSystem, Duty, HohfeldianPosition, Breach, Sanction, Rule, Judgment, Authority" ;
  schema:identifier &lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/sociology/domains/work/domains/governance/terms/norm-conflict/> .

